<section xmlns="http://xml.house.gov/schemas/uslm/1.0" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="-uslm-lc:I80" id="idef8eb10a-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db" identifier="/us/usc/t54/s102502"><num value="102502">§ 102502.</num><heading> Definition of museum object</heading>
<chapeau style="-uslm-lc:I11" class="indent0">In this chapter:</chapeau><paragraph style="-uslm-lc:I12" class="indent1" id="idef8eb10b-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db" identifier="/us/usc/t54/s102502/1"><num value="1">(1)</num><heading> <inline class="small-caps">In general</inline>.—</heading><chapeau>The term “museum object” means an object that—</chapeau><subparagraph style="-uslm-lc:I13" class="indent2" id="idef8eb10c-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db" identifier="/us/usc/t54/s102502/1/A"><num value="A">(A)</num><content> typically is movable; and</content>
</subparagraph>
<subparagraph style="-uslm-lc:I13" class="indent2" id="idef8eb10d-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db" identifier="/us/usc/t54/s102502/1/B"><num value="B">(B)</num><content> is eligible to be, or is made part of, a museum, library, or archive collection through a formal procedure, such as accessioning.</content>
</subparagraph>
</paragraph>
<paragraph style="-uslm-lc:I12" class="indent1" id="idef8eb10e-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db" identifier="/us/usc/t54/s102502/2"><num value="2">(2)</num><heading> <inline class="small-caps">Inclusions</inline>.—</heading><content>The term “museum object” includes a prehistoric or historic artifact, work of art, book, document, photograph, or natural history specimen.</content>
</paragraph>
<sourceCredit id="idef8eb10f-3a70-11f1-83cd-8a39f388f6db">(<ref href="/us/pl/113/287/s3">Pub. L. 113–287, § 3</ref>, <date date="2014-12-19">Dec. 19, 2014</date>, <ref href="/us/stat/128/3157">128 Stat. 3157</ref>.)</sourceCredit>
